pr_review_comment_body:
Few remarks more:
- `import importlib` doesn't look neccessary;
- Where `__file__` comes from?

To save yourself from having to use .bind(this) everywhere, typically should just save a reference to this in a variable called `self` at the top of the function like such:

```js
Adams.prototype.lookup = function() {
  var self = this; // save reference to this out here
  
  // can continue to use this on this level (self is the same)
  this.datastore.datasets.lookup({ /* options */ }, function(err, result) {
    if(err) {
      // but in the anonymous function, use self because this now points to something else
      self.emit('error', err);
    }
  }); // no bind :) much cleaner
}

@kalefranz , the test fails in this line 

    assert "packaged by conda-forge" in sys_version, sys_version

The python is still in default channel, seems we need to activate env to work. Maybe we can use the get_conda_list_tuple method, and check the 4th element is 'conda-forge'. Just like how we check the version of pycosat.

Shouldn't `sUsbState.mOpenTimestamp` be checked here as well? If there were no queued data and we call `otPlatUartSend` just after the port is opened we will send it without waiting the `USB_HOST_UART_CONFIG_DELAY_MS `.

I can see though, that in case we check for this in `otPlatUartSend`, the time checking logic should be protected against timer overflow, something like:
```
bool hasPortOpenDelayPassed(void)
{
    int32_t timeDiff = otPlatAlarmMilliGetNow() - sUsbState.mOpenTimestamp;

    return (timeDiff < 0) || (timeDiff > USB_HOST_UART_CONFIG_DELAY_MS);
}
```
